    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "description",
      "value": "Design and execute a diagnostic test to detect k-point convergence failures caused by DFT band-gap underestimation in VASP calculations. The test compares convergence behavior (total energy vs. k-point density) for a known insulator (SrTiO₃) using PBE (which underestimates the gap) and HSE06 (which corrects it), fitting the convergence curves to exponential vs. power-law models to identify false convergence signals."
    },
    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "expected_prediction",
      "value": "For SrTiO₃ with PBE (underestimated gap ~1.9 eV vs. experimental 3.25 eV), the total energy convergence with k-points will follow a power-law decay (~1/N_k) characteristic of metallic systems, giving a false positive for convergence at moderate k-point density. With HSE06 (corrected gap ~3.2 eV), the convergence will follow exponential decay (~exp(-α·N_k^{1/3})), requiring significantly fewer k-points for true convergence. The diagnostic metric — ratio of convergence rate between PBE and HSE06 — will be >3× for the same apparent convergence threshold, exposing the blind spot."
    },
    {
      "@type": "PropertyValue",
      "name": "plan_id",
      "value": "plan_6b20d1db"
    }
  ],
